	<div class="article">
					<h2><a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2006/07/easy_local_and_remote_backup_of_your_home_network/">Easy local and remote backup of your home network</a></h2>
			<address class="vcard">by <a href="http://www.jejik.com/authors/sander_marechal/" class="url fn">Sander Marechal</a></address>
			<p><em>Updated on 2006-09-20 to add an exclude file and clear up some rsync confusion</em></p>

<p>I hate making backups by hand. It costs a lot of time and usually I have far better things to do. Luckily GNU/Linux comes with all the tools you need to backup your machines automatically and wide availability of broadband make it possible to have remote backups as well - to a friend's place for example.</p>

<p>This article will show you how to set up fast, fully automated local and remote backups for a small home network using standard GNU/Linux tools.</p>				<div class="postinfo">
			Posted on 2006-07-25@20:33
							<img src="/images/icons/document.png" alt="" />
				<a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2006/07/easy_local_and_remote_backup_of_your_home_network/">read more</a>
				<img src="/images/icons/comments.png" alt="" />
				<a href="http://www.jejik.com/articles/2006/07/easy_local_and_remote_backup_of_your_home_network/#comments">2 comments</a>
